        "id": 283189,
        "name": "Talya (she/her)",
        "username": "rassilon1963",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/rassilon1963/{size}/31625_2.png",
        "created_at": "2026-01-21T18:36:10.639Z",
        "cooked": "<p>i‚Äôd say there‚Äôs three kinds of criticisms, two valid and one that‚Äôs not valid but still sadly common.</p>\n<p>i‚Äôll start with the one that isn‚Äôt valid: ‚ÄúSignal can be hacked‚Äù. that‚Äôs what you touched on here:</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"ret_ff17\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"74380\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/ret_ff17/48/49655_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> ret_ff17:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Signal offers one of the (if not the) strongest encryption in the world and is now quantum proof even for hack now harvest later protection.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>it‚Äôs one many reporters unfortunately fall into, but it fully misses the point, which is that Signal is by far <em>not</em> the weakest link in this chain, so the likelihood of a state actor trying to hack it specifically rather than use the much easier target that is the phone is very small.</p>\n<p>one criticism that is valid is coming back to that last part, which is that the weakest link is the phone. your point that</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"ret_ff17\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"74380\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/ret_ff17/48/49655_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> ret_ff17:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>they‚Äôre using gov managed (enterprise grade) Apple hardware that is most likely in Lockdown mode at all times.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>is only true if using a mobile phone for secure communication was part of the security plan, which, speaking from experience, it very often isn‚Äôt. depending on the security model of the organisation it may be okay, or patently illegal. some security situations ask for sensitive information to be talked about in strictly air-gapped systems, which a mobile phone, even in lockdown mode, isn‚Äôt.<br>\nso some conversations fit Signal with lockdown mode, some don‚Äôt.</p>\n<p>but the third and final criticism is the most interesting one, because it‚Äôs not about security at all, but rather about documentation. many countries have laws mandating that some or all internal government communications be preserved in posterity, which Signal isn‚Äôt built for. first because it‚Äôs not the kind of communication app that constantly backs itself up to secure government storage (and when you try to do it <a href=\"https://www.404media.co/the-signal-clone-the-trump-admin-uses-was-hacked/\">you often do it wrong</a>), but second, you can easily delete messages without leaving a trace on your device, which is the opposite of what we want.</p>\n<p>so the tl;dr is there‚Äôs nothing wrong with government officials using Signal ‚Äî when they‚Äôre legally allowed to. however in many of the recently publicised cases they weren‚Äôt allowed to, and that‚Äôs exactly the point journalists should focus on.</p>",
